Rating: 4
For most of my dessert eating life, I've made and ordered rich, chocolate sweets. Lately, I've been branching out, and I'm glad I tried this frozen Grand Marnier torte for Christmas, which I found in the Holiday Dessert slideshow on Bon Appetit's website. As soon as I saw this colorful and unique dish, I knew it was the one! It does have a chocolate cookie crust, the flavor of which comes through with a crunchy finish, but there are a lot of tastes and textures in each bite. Its absolutely delicious! Heres the link. Another plus is that most of the ingredients in this recipe are fairly inexpensive, as opposed to, say, all the cheese in cheesecake. You will have to invest in some Port and orange liquor, but there'll be plenty left. I didnt use Grand Marnier b/c it costs more than similar liquors and we have a local product, Paulas Texas Orange. Also, instead of a true Port, which comes from Portugal, I went with a local wine, Torre di Pietras Tango Port. We drank the extra, which was the perfect compliment to the dessert, especially since it was too late for coffee. I agree with others that the cranberry overpowered the filling, although I wish I had read these reviews before I made it. :) Next time I will try substituting other fruit. I was thinking of apples or oranges as well as raspberries. Bon Appetit says the recipe is easy, and I would mostly agree. I had one difficulty, I wasnt sure how stiffly to beat the whipping cream and sour cream, and there wasnt much guidance. But I just went with my gut and it turned out great! This dessert was fun to make, festive and was a hit with my friends. We did not have a cranberry dish with the Christmas dinner and I was glad to be able to incorporate the traditional fruit into dessert. I would certainly make this again!

